    "summary": "Lagash, located in what is now southeastern Iraq near the confluence of the Shatt al-Gharraf and Shatt al-Hai rivers, was one of the major city-states of ancient Sumer, with early occupation extending back to at least 3500 BCE. The city gained its greatest prominence during the Early Dynastic period of the third millennium BCE, when it was the center of an independent kingdom and left extensive records of Sumerian administration, law, and religion. Its early development during the fourth millennium BCE placed it within the network of emerging Sumerian urban centers clustered in the rich agricultural lands of the lower Mesopotamian alluvial plain.\n\nLagash was actually a district comprising several urban centers including the city of Girsu (modern Telloh), which was the administrative capital, and Lagash proper (modern Al-Hiba), which was the main harbor settlement. The city's location near the marshlands of southern Mesopotamia gave it access to abundant fish, reeds, and waterfowl alongside the agricultural potential of the irrigated fields between its rivers. The city's patron deity was Ningirsu, a war god and lord of the thunderstorm, whose temple at Girsu was an important cultic center.\n\nLagash is particularly significant to historians because of the extraordinarily large archive of cuneiform tablets recovered from Girsu, including records from the reign of the reforming ruler Urukagina (c. 2350 BCE) who issued what some scholars consider the world's earliest known law code addressing social abuses and corruption. The city's archaeological record thus provides an unusually detailed window into Sumerian administrative and social practice across multiple centuries.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagash",
